4. Introduction

This document is dedicated for system integrators and client / user interface developers. It explains how to use the communication object of the Comet JSON-RPC interface. The goal is to understand the following:

  • organization and patterns of communication objects
  • communication object polling and state change detection
  • typical use cases of interactions between client and device

The communication interface specification is organized by layers, see the diagram below. The Comet-specific layers (yellow) are on top of the standard protocol layers (grey). Each of the Comet-specific layer corresponds to a given protocol abstraction, and has its own document.

5. References

Comet-specific layer specifications:

  • JSON-RPC Protocol Specification
  • Communication Object Specification

6. Object Patterns

In the Comet-specific JSON-RPC-layer there is no support for accessing complex nested JSON-objects. Only arrays of simple JSON-types (like Number, String and Bool) are supported. More complex structures are expressed by using multiple such simple objects, based on the object/resource name and its hierarchy. This is what is called a pattern.

This chapter introduces a few common patterns for expressing more complex data in a "standard" way.

The syntax of pattern description is the following:

resource0: typeDescription0, access0
resource1: typeDescription1, access1
...
resourceN-1: typeDescriptionN-1, accessN-1

Every line represents a simple object. Together, they represent a complex object.

6.1. Array

6.1.1. Overview

  • An Array is a one-dimensional list of values with a common type
  • An Array can have a dynamic length
  • An Array can be accessed by reading (r) and/or writing (w) it
  • An Array can only be accessed as a whole - individual field access is not possible

6.1.2. Resource representation

<resource>: <type>[length], <access>

6.1.3. Example

/device/tube/focalSpotSizes: number[5], r

6.2. Simple Object

6.2.1. Overview

  • A Simple Object is represented by an array of length 1

6.2.2. Resource representation

<resource>: <type>[1], <access>

6.2.3. Example

/operation/setpoint/polarity: number[1], rw

6.3. 1D-Table

6.3.1. Overview

  • A 1D-Table is equivalent to an Array, with the addition of field names
  • It is useful in cases when it is not obvious what each field in an Array represents or if the Array's size or content is dynamic

6.3.2. Resource representation

<resource>/xNames: string[xLen], <access>
<resource>: <type>[xLen], <access>

6.3.3. Example

/system/network/ip/settings/xNames: string[3], r
/system/network/ip/settings: string[3], rw

6.4. 2D-Table

6.4.1. Overview

  • A 2D-Table is organized in groups of fields along the Y-axis
  • A 2D-Table has a fixed number of groups, which corrsponds with the X-length
  • The length (number of fields) of a group can be dynamic
  • All groups in the same 2D-Table must be equal in length
  • Each group can be of a different type
  • Only whole groups can be accessed at once - individual field access is not possible
  • Each group is mapped to an explicit resource (no explicit length is given)
  • xNames and yNames (field names) are provided by the pattern

The 2D-Table is used when fields need to be organized in two-dimensional space, and accessed atomically in groups. It is not well suited if the ability to write to single fields is needed, since that would require a read-modify-write sequence of the entire group.

6.4.2. Resource representation

<resource>/xNames: string[xLen], <access>
<resource>/yNames: string[yLen], <access>

<resource>/<xName0>: <xType0>[yLen], <access>
<resource>/<xName1>: <xType1>[yLen], <access>
...
<resource>/<xName<xLen>-1>: <xType<xLen>-1>[yLen], <access>

6.4.3. Example

/operation/supervision/device/xNames: string[5], r 
-> ["states", "details", "rankings", "timestamps", "shutdownReasons"]
/operation/supervision/device/yNames: string[64], r 
-> ["device", "device/ctlDevLs", "device/ctlDevLs/anode", "device/ctlDevLs/cathode" ...]

/operation/supervision/device/states: number[64], r
/operation/supervision/device/details: number[64], r
/operation/supervision/device/rankings: number[64], r
/operation/supervision/device/timestamps: number[64], r
/operation/supervision/device/shutdownReasons: number[64], r

Below is suggested pseudo-code to read a 2D-Table dynamically and store it in the dict-variable table:

xNames = read('/operation/supervision/device/xNames')
table = {}
for xName in xNames:
   table[xName] = read('/operation/supervision/device/' + xName)

But typically clients may read or write 2D-tables statically, and only partially, e.g.:

currentStates = read('/operation/supervision/device/states')
currentDetails = read('/operation/supervision/device/details')

6.5. 3D-Table

6.5.1. Overview

  • A 3D-Table is organized in groups of fields along the Z-axis
  • A 3D-Table has a fixed number of groups, which corrsponds with the X- and Y-lengths
  • The length (number of fields) of a group can be dynamic
  • Only whole groups can be accessed at once - individual field access is not possible
  • Each group can be of a different type, but it must be common for all groups along the Y-axis
  • Each combination of an X-name and a Y-name is an explicit resource that corresponds to a certain group
  • xNames, yNames and zNames (field names) are provided by the pattern

The 3D-table is used when multiple groups need to be organized in two-dimensional space, resulting in a three dimensional arrangement of the individual fields. Each group is only accessible explicitly by its X- and Y-name.

6.5.2. Resource representation

For readability the lengths along X/Y/Z-axis is defined as L/M/N here:

In this example, the group's types are common along the Y-axis

<resource>/xNames: <string>[L], <access>
<resource>/yNames: <string>[M], <access>
<resource>/zNames: <string>[N], <access>


<resource>/<xName0>/<yName0>: <xType0>[N], <access>
<resource>/<xName0>/<yName1>: <xType0>[N], <access>
...
<resource>/<xName0>/<yNameM-1>: <xType0>[N], <access>

<resource>/<xName1>/<yName0>: <xType1>[N], <access>
<resource>/<xName1>/<yName1>: <xType1>[N], <access>
...
<resource>/<xName1>/<yNameM-1>: <xType1>[N], <access>

...

<resource>/<xNameL-1>/<yName0>: <xTypeL-1>[N], <access>
<resource>/<xNameL-1>/<yName1>: <xTypeL-1>[N], <access>
...
<resource>/<xNameL-1>/<yNameM-1>: <xTypeL-1>[N], <access>

6.5.3. Example

/configuration/inventory/xNames: string[21], r
-> ["module", "ccm", "apm", ...]
/configuration/inventory/yNames: string[8], r
-> ["category", "variant", "uid", "version", "material", "date"]
/configuration/inventory/zNames: string[1], r
-> [""]

/configuration/inventory/module/category: number[1], r
/configuration/inventory/module/variant: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/module/uid: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/module/version: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/module/material: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/module/date: number[1], r

/configuration/inventory/ccm/category: number[1], r
/configuration/inventory/ccm/variant: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/ccm/uid: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/ccm/version: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/ccm/material: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/ccm/date: number[1], r

/configuration/inventory/apm/category: number[1], r
/configuration/inventory/apm/variant: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/apm/uid: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/apm/version: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/apm/material: string[1], r
/configuration/inventory/apm/date: number[1], r

Below is suggested pseudo-code to read a 3D-table dynamically into the dictionary table:

xNames = read('/configuration/inventory/xNames')
yNames = read('/configuration/inventory/yNames')
zNames = read('/configuration/inventory/zNames')
table = {}
for xName in xNames:   
   row = {}
   for yName in yNames:
      row[yName] = read('/configuration/inventory/' + xName + '/' + yName)
   table[xName] = row

Alternatively, clients may read or write 3D-tables statically, and only partially, e.g.:

version = read('/configuration/inventory/module/version')

7. Synchronization

7.1. Operation UID

The internal design of the device is inherently asynchronous. Not only the communication path is asynchronous and running multithreaded, but also all the business logic inside. This makes it harder for the client to perform consecutive and sequential operations within narrow timing constraints. The problem is that the "before operation" may look the same as the "after operation".

The unique ID (UID) concept helps to differentiate this. The client produces an UID, propagates it via operation request, and read it back via operation confirm. The propagation inside the device is only performed when the corresponding operation is executed. This provides evidence to the client, that its operation is executing or has been executed. With this help, the client is capable of synchronize consecutive and sequential operations.

To synchronize entire operations the UID is propagated from operation request (/operation/control/request) to operation confirm (/operation/control/confirm) as explained above. To synchronize workpoint changes within an operation, the same UID object is used, but this time from setpoint trigger (/operation/setpoint/applyValues/trigger) to operation confirm (/operation/control/confirm).

UID synchronization is only supported for explicitly applied setpoints (by writing trigger). When automatic/implicitly applied, then workpoint change synchronization via UID is not supported (see chapter User Changes Nominal Setpoints).

8. Throughput Optimization

8.1. Overview

The JSON-RPC protocol does currently not provide any publish/subscribe mechanism or any kind of event notification from the device to a client. So the client needs to do expensive polling to detect changes.

The main goal of this optimization is to minimize communication throughput on device side, since the device has limited CPU and memory resource available. At object level, the following concepts are provided for reducing the data volume to transfer:

  • Constant objects for handle never changing data
  • Hash for handle rarely changing data or events

8.2. Constant Objects

Objects that are marked both as r and const only need to be read once during runtime. The value is guaranteed to remain constant (for a given device of course). Typical const objects are for example names or an array of names. Thus clients do not need to read those names again and again. Clients shall cache these values.

Consider value change only for the following cases:

  • after device reboot
  • after a software-update

8.3. Hash

Some of the table instances contain data that do not often change. To prevent polling of the entire table content, to find out if any of the data have changed, some tables provide an optional Hash object:

<resource>/hash: number[1], r

The client only needs to poll this hash object, and remember its value. When the value changes from one poll to the next, then this means that something has changed in the table. So the client needs to re-read the table only in that case. The value of the hash has no specific meaning.

The hash is guaranteed to change when the data in table has changed. But there is no reverse guarantee: It is tolerated for the hash to change from time to time, despite no data in the table changed, as long as the false positives do not get too expensive.

For the list of tables that support hashes please refer to the Communication Object Specification.

Below is suggested pseudo-code:

def pollTable():
   newHash = readHashOnly()
   if newHash != oldHash:
      readEntireTableExcludingConstObjects()
      oldHash = newHash

Examples of tables featuring the hash mechanism:

  • /operation/setpoint/appliedLimits/workPoint
  • /operation/setpoint/appliedLimits/extrema
  • /operation/supervision/device
  • /device/sensor/alarm/state

9. Use Cases

9.1. Overview

Lets have a look at specific application examples of how to control the device from a client's point of view. The absolute minimum client functionality for operation shall cover the following use cases:

  • User Changes Nominal Setpoints
  • User Starts / Stops Operation

When more transparency is required, like presenting status information, so that the user understands what is going on, then the client shall cover the following use cases too:

  • Read Operation Confirm
  • Display Supervision States
  • and optionally Display Current Measurements

These use cases are not coupled at all. They can be applied concurrently, in an entirely asynchronous and decoupled way. For example polling supervision states, displaying current measurements, start/stop operation and changing nominal setpoints can be applied from different threads on client side.

It is important to understand, that the client does not need to track any state machine or respect any sequence to perform single operations. The client can just request any of the allowed operation at any time.

9.2. User Changes Nominal Setpoints

The user changes nominal setpoints, like HV and emission. This can be performed independently of the current running operation. In case of HV and/or emission currently being off, the new value is remembered for the next time such an operation starts. The latest applied relevant setpoints are even stored persistently. In case of x-ray currently being on, the setpoint changes lead to an immediate start of ramping towards these new setpoints.

The user may change these setpoints at any time: during off, during on, during ongoing ramps and so on. When the device is on and not in a warmup-situation, it tries to apply the setpoint as fast as possible, by interrupting possible current ongoing ramps, and start moving towards the new setpoints.

There are two ways of applying setpoint changes:

  • automatic/implicitly, when corresponding setpoint is written
  • explicitly, by writing trigger object

Below the pseudo-code for changing setpoints, when apply values is automatic:

write('/operation/setpoint/values/hv', 50000.0)
write('/operation/setpoint/values/emission', 0.000200)

The setpoints are applied at individual points of time, according to the corresponding write accesses.

There is also the possibility to apply multiple setpoints atomically at the same time. For this the apply values automatic mode must be disabled:

write('/operation/setpoint/applyValues/auto', False)

And in addition, every group of setpoint changes must be triggered explicitly in this way:

write('/operation/setpoint/values/hv', 50000.0)
write('/operation/setpoint/values/emission', 0.000200)
write('/operation/setpoint/applyValues/trigger', 789)

The setpoints are now applied all at the exact same point in time, when accessing the trigger. The value passed when calling trigger is an UID, which can be read back in operation confirm.

9.3. User Starts / Stops Operation

In a regular case, for some products, after powerup, the device starts heating the emitter. Depending on the product and its configuration, a heater-warmup sequence is implicitly started.

After the heater-warmup sequence, an optional pre-warning and a warmup sequence is performed. Once these sequences are over, the device is ready for immediate x-ray operation.

Independent of the above mentioned sequences the user can request the xray on operation. The device remembers that request, and it will end in this operation once optional and time-consuming...

  • heater-warmup
  • pre-warning
  • warmup

...are complete. If the device was already heated and warmup was not required, then the xray on operation starts immediately.

If the user changes his mind and decides to not start x-ray but requests another operation, like heater on, then a current ongoing warmup-sequence is interrupted, and the device gently ramps down both HV and emission. So the device is capable to interrupt any ongoing ramp or sequence at any time.

If the user wants to shutdown as fast as possible, then he needs to request the operation shutdown to heater on. The difference between gently move to heater on and shutdown to heater on as fast as possible, is the time it takes.

The diagram below shows a simplified state machine, which represents the operation behaviour on the device.

Below the pseudo-code for starting xray on:

write('/operation/control/request', 30h)

Below the pseudo-code for stopping xray on, and go back to heater on:

write('/operation/control/request', 10h)

Below the pseudo-code for shutting down to heater on:

write('/operation/control/request', 2h)

Below the pseudo-code for starting xray on, uniquely identified as 777. It is recommended to change to a new UID on each request. The value of the UID has no specific meaning:

write('/operation/control/request', [30h, 777])

9.4. Display Currently Allowed Operations

Use this functionality to list allowed operations. In some conditions, like if an error is pending or when a error state, operations may not be allowed. The client could use this information to enable/disable operation buttons in the GUI.

Below the pseudo-code to determine whether the given operation is currently allowed or not:

   allowedOperations = read('/operation/control/allowed')
   if 30h is in allowedOperations:
      #xray-on is currently allowed...
   else:
      #xray-on is not allowed...

Here an overview of allowed operations in function of the current operation:

9.5. Read Back Operation Request

Another way for the client to ensure if the request was allowed, is to read back the operation request. The client will only read back the written request value if the request was allowed and applied.

Below the pseudo-code for ensuring xray on was allowed and has been applied:

write('/operation/control/request', 30h)
if read('/operation/control/request')[0] == 30h:
   #all ok...
else:
   #request was not accepted...

9.6. Read Operation Confirm

If the client needs to know more accurately the current ongoing sequence, or needs to synchronize the end of operation with the start of a next one, e.g. for seamless sequences, then he can read the object operation confirm. For example this shows which intermediate/implicit operation is currently going on, like a pre-warning or short warmup.

The operation confirm contains the UID, which is owned by the client, and has been set during a request. By reading back the client is capable to associate a consecutive same current operation confirm with a given request. This is helpful since the communication is heavily asychronous, and there is no guarantee that after writing a request, the state has already updated at all. Not having the UID would make it impossible to recognize between "before request" and "when done".

The UID can also be used to recognize if the current ongoing sequence is still on the "right path" of the initial request or not. The UID value changes to zero on unsolicited operation interruption due to a supervision error.

The operation confirm also contains the phase information, which shows if the requested setpoints are currently reached or not:

  • ramping
  • reached

These 3 informations (confirmed operation, UID and phase) are provided in an atomic access. The sequence diagram below shows the transition behaviour of an operation:

Below the pseudo-code for reading operation confirm:

cf = read('/operation/control/confirm')
confirmedOperation = cf[0]
uid = cf[1]
phase = cf[2]
#do what ever with the confirmed value cf...

9.7. Synchronize To Operation End

If the client wants to perform any action which is synchronous to an operation ending, then the following procedure is proposed:

  • apply individual UID per operation request
  • poll the /operation/control/confirm object...
    • until the goal is reached...
      • the destination operation is set AND the phase is reached AND the UID matches the requested one
    • OR until the operation was interrupted...
      • the destination operation is unexpectedly off or heater on AND the phase is reached AND the UID is zero
    • OR until timeout...
      • e.g. when operation was not started since not allowed

The destination operation depends on the operation, if it's a self-terminating one or not.

Below the pseudo-code for waiting until operation is done:

#synchronize with operation end...
def waitUntilDone():
   startTimeout()
   while not isTimeout():
      if (confirmedOp == expectedOp) AND (phase == <reached>) AND (uid == requestedUid):
         return ok
      sleep(pollingPeriod)
   return failedDueToTimeout

9.8. Display Supervision States

When it comes to displaying the supervision state of the device, we must understand how it is organized:

  • the supervision state consists of a tree of hierarchical device units
  • every leaf unit represents a part of the device or a function of the device
  • each unit may be in one of these states:
state id reaction on current operation duration impact on next operation recovering conditions examples
ready 0x1
warning 0x2 no reaction remains until ok again allows to start warning condition gone Temperature slightly too high, Power supply too low, Warm-up required, ...
user-clearable error 0x3 stops current operation remains until user acknowledgement cannot start explicit acknowledge: /operation/supervision/clear Too many arcs in a specific period of time, protection triggered, ...
self-clearable error 0x4 stops current operation remains until ok again cannot start error condition is gone Temperature too high, Client-to-ConDev guard error, ...
non-clearable error 0x5 stops current operation remains until reboot cannot start reboot and error condition is gone Communication between ConDev and CtlDev interrupted, Corrupted data, ConDev-to-CtlDev guard error, ...
  • the ID represents the severity level, from best (0x1) to worst (0x5)
  • the parent units summarizes and represent the worst state of its children. So the worst state is propagated upstream the tree, up to root
  • every leaf unit contains a detail information of the current warning or error
  • every leaf unit contains the ranking number, representing the chronological sequence order of occurance, including a timestamp
  • last but not least, every node has a name which is organized as a path, representing the location in the tree from root
  • all this information is collected in the table /operation/supervision/device
  • as a general rule, the first unit of this table is the root element

The table is organized in a flat linear way, but the model of the units is based on a tree. the client has several options how to represent the supervision:

  • as a tree
  • as a list
  • as a simple state

For this to happen, the client needs to read the node's names, analyze the path information in the name, and reconstruct/reorganize the nodes in the way he wants. This results in a "reindexing" of the nodes on client-side. This has to be done only once after reboot, since the unit names are constant.

9.8.1. As A Tree

To represent the table as a tree, the client needs to reconstruct the tree with the help of the nodes' names (by starting from root and matching the path elements excluding the last element with the already collected nodes)

9.8.2. As A List

To represent the table as a list, the client may optionally skip all intermediate / parent nodes. They can be identified with the help of the nodes' names (by identifying node names being a substring of leaf names or not)

9.8.3. As A Simple State

If only a simple state needs to be presented, then you can present the root node only. It is simply the first unit in the table. Since parent nodes' states represent the worst (most severe) state of their children, the root node presents a global state. But in that case, the result contains no information about what goes wrong.

9.8.4. Usage

The supervision table needs to be polled. For throughput optimization reasons, this table has a hash object for effective polling. This is explained in the chapter about hash above.

Below is suggested pseudo-code for displaying the supervision results:

def initializeSupervision():
   names = read('/operation/supervision/device/yNames')
   indexes = generateRowReindexingAccordingToPresentation(names)

def pollSupervision():
   newHash = read('/operation/supervision/device/hash')[0]
   if newHash != oldHash:
      states = read('/operation/supervision/device/states')
      details = read('/operation/supervision/device/details')
      rankings = read('/operation/supervision/device/rankings')
      timestamps = read('/operation/supervision/device/timestamps')
      shutdownReasons = read('/operation/supervision/device/shutdownReasons')
      presentTheNodeOrganization(indexes, names, states, details, ...)
      oldHash = newHash

The details of generateRowReindexingAccordingToPresentation() are not explained in this document. Depending on the chosen presentation this may be the costly part. Luckily it can be optimized, by performing it only once after bootup.

All the reindexing-complexity can be skipped if you decide to present the supervision units as a list, including the parent nodes.

The details of presentTheNodeOrganization() are not explained in this document too.

9.9. Display Supervision Ranking

To represent the units ordered by ranking, the flat table can be sorted in function of the ranking and only include units with a ranking order greater than zero.

9.10. Display Current Applied Setpoints

Depending on the visualization requirements, a client may want to present the setpoint values that will be applied on next operation, considering limits, mode, polarity... etc. This information is available in the table /operation/setpoint/appliedValues.

Below is suggested pseudo-code for reading out applied setpoint values:

setpoints = read('/operation/setpoint/appliedValues')
heaterSetpoint = setpoints[0]
hvSetpoint = setpoints[1]
emissionSetpoint = setpoints[2]

9.11. Display Current Action Setpoints

Depending on the visualization requirements, a client may want to present the setpoint values that are currently active or currently ramping to, considering the current operation step. This information is available in the table /operation/setpoint/actionValues.

Below is suggested pseudo-code for reading out action setpoints:

setpoints = read('/operation/setpoint/actionValues')
heaterSetpoint = setpoints[0]
hvSetpoint = setpoints[1]
emissionSetpoint = setpoints[2]

9.12. Display Current Measurements

The current measured values of heater, HV and emission can be read out via the following object:

/device/sensor/meas/values

Below is suggested pseudo-code for reading out controller measurements:

measurements = read('/device/controller/ctlDevLs/acquisition')
heater = measurements[4]
hv = measurements[0]
emission = measurements[2]

9.13. Display Applied Limits

The applied limits are presented in the webUI, as this characteristic shape in the workpoint-diagram.

The currently applied limits have tube, tank, user, focalspot considered. This can be read out via the following tables:

  • /operation/setpoint/appliedLimits/workPoint
  • /operation/setpoint/appliedLimits/extrema

Both tables contain the hash object for efficient polling. workPoint contains the actual workpoint-segment-curve of 5 points. extrema contains the actual min/max-values for all setpoints.

In addition the object /operation/setpoint/appliedLimits/valid represents the validity of these limits. Depending the values of the combined limits, the resulting surface in the workpoint-area may be zero, so those limits become invalid. (For example, when one limit's extrema maximum is lower than the other limit's extrema minimum.)

9.14. Display Tube Limits

The tube limits can be read out via the following tables:

  • /device/tube/limits/workPoint
  • /device/tube/limits/extrema

Both tables contain tube-specific limits in function of focalspots. workPoint contains one workpoint-segment-curve of 5 points per focalspot. extrema contains min/max-values for all setpoints per focalspot.

9.18. Display Versions

The version and all other inventory information of all components can be found in the table /configuration/inventory.

xNames = read('/configuration/inventory/xNames')
yNames = read('/configuration/inventory/yNames')
inventory = []
for xName in xNames:   
   item = {}
   for yName in yNames:
      item[yName] = read('/configuration/inventory/'+ xName +'/'+ yName)
   inventory.append(item)

9.19. Perform SW Update

The sw-update procedure is somewhat more challenging, since it is made of several steps, with the device rebooting inbetween, and so the client needs to reconnect automatically.

The client needs to:

  • ensure the device operation is off
  • set the device in maintenance mode
  • download zip-archive software package to /flash/package/package.zip on the target
  • optionally read the package information on the device
  • start the sw-update procedure
  • poll the sw-update state until idle
    • reconnect in case of connection loss
  • verify the sw-update result for done or failed
  • report the result

Optionally the progress can be polled on target and presented to the user.

Here the pseudo code:

#switch off...
write('/operation/control/request', 0) 
wait until read('/operation/control/confirm')[0] == 0

#start maintenance...
write('/operation/control/request', 8) 
wait until read('/operation/control/confirm')[0] == 8

#download package...
writeFileToTarget(swPackageZipFile)

#install package...
write('/system/swUpdate/control', 1)
wait until read('/system/swUpdate/result') != 0

return result

The following is not expressed at all in the pseudo code:

  • challenge of reconnecting after timeout
  • package information read out of target
  • read and calculate progress

Have a look in the python reference implementation in novello/console.py.

9.20. Upload Log

The log is stored in multiple files on the device. Those files are organized in a file rotation way: The oldest file is deleted when a new file is created. The client needs to:

  • disable the running log on the device, to have atomic access
  • read the list of file paths to upload
  • sort the list chronologically
  • upload each file of that list
  • enable the running log again
  • concatenate the uploaded files to one big file
  • clean up the uploaded small files
  • output the concatenated file

Here the pseudo code:

#disable log and wait for flushing...
write('/system/log/enable', false)
sleep(fewSeconds)

#read the file list and sort chronologically...
paths = read('/system/log/paths')
paths.sortLastPathElementAlphabetically()
paths.sortFirstFlashThenEepromPaths()

#upload file by file and merge them...
mergedFile = createNewEmptyMergedFile()
for p in paths:
   tmpFile = readFileFromTarget(p)
   mergeTmpFileToMergedFile()

#re-enable log...
write('/system/log/enable', true)

#cleanup...
cleanUpTmpFile()
return mergedFile

Have a look in the python reference implementation in novello/console.py.

9.21. System Sets Date and Time on Device

The date/time of the device can be set via the object /system/dateTime. This supports unsigned 64bit value range. It represents local time. The unit corresponds to epoch, in milliseconds. The client may adjust the date/time from time to time. But it is not recommended to adjust this at very high rate, it is better to limit this to once in a week or even fewer.

Below is suggested pseudo-code for adjusting the time to 2022-03-09 18:51:00.000:

write('/system/dateTime', 1646848260000)

Date/time may need to be adjusted after a power-off duration of around more than 6 months, since after such long power-off durations the device may freeze or even loose its date/time.

9.22. Enable Network Guard between Client and Device

A client may want to guard the communication connection between client and device. When enabling this guard, both partners of the connection are able to react locally on broken connection:

  • the client may show in the user interface that the device is dead
  • the device shuts down operation automatically when the client is dead from its point of view

If the client wants to disconnect on purpose and gracefully, then it needs to disable the guard before disconnecting.

This guard concept makes sense for one single client guarding only. The concept does not work for guarding multiple clients and expecting to react when only one of them gets offline.

The guard can be controlled by the client via /system/network/guard/conDev/....

Below is suggested pseudo-code to periodically polling the device:

def startGuarding():
   #configure the timeout to around two times the poll-period...
   write('/system/network/guard/conDev/timeout', 4.0) 
   #start...
   write('/system/network/guard/conDev/enable', True)

def pollGuardPeriodically():
   """
   call periodically, with a period of 2 seconds
   """
   try:
      result = read('/system/network/guard/conDev/poll')
      if result == oldResult:
         raise exception
      oldResult = result
      #react due to device is alive here...
   except:
      #react due to device is dead here...

def stopGuarding():
   write('/system/network/guard/conDev/enable', False)

9.23. Edit User Config File

A client may want to manage custom settings (e.g. user setpoint limits). These can be written to a config-file, to be downloaded on the device. The config file is a json-file and has the following structure:

{
    "metaVersion": "V.2.0",
    "compatibility": [
        {
            "name": "conApp",
            "minVersion": "B.2"
        }
    ],
    "configuration": [
        {
            "entry": [
                {
                    "resource": "/user/limits/extrema/hv",
                    "value": [0.0, 720000.0]
                },
                {
                    "resource": "/user/limits/extrema/emission",
                    "value": [0.0, 0.01]
                },
                {
                    "resource": "/user/limits/extrema/power",
                    "value": [0.0, 5000.0]
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

metaVersion and compatibility consist of the header, and shall not be modified by the user.

entry is an array of custom settings to be applied at startup. Each entry consists of a resource to be accessed, and a value to write to. The resources are specified in the Communication Object Specification . Only resources marked with Persistence userConfig are supported.

The file is located on the target and is accessible via file access (refer to JSON-RPC Protocol Specification) at the fix location /flash/config/custom/userConfig.json. It can be read and written to.
